tweet: So, Coin Center looks forward to engaging with the various agencies now tasked with studying and planning on the issues we‚Äôve spent nearly a decade working on, as well as engaging with thought legislative proposal from serious leaders in Congress.

tweet: The EO also presents another striking contrast with alarmist politicians and media in that it is ultimately a call for further study and deliberate planning, not a reactive rush to legislate or regulate.

tweet: 2/ If the provision included by Rep. @jahimes in the America COMPETES Act becomes law, Treasury will no longer have to publish any such list. It would not have notify the public or seek public comment. It will be able to take "special measures" in secret.

name: Jerry Brito
tweet: 1/ Because Treasury is required under current law to notify the public and seek public input whenever it takes "special measures" we have a nice list of how it's employing this power. Important way for the public to check its government. https://t.co/wB4saZpvkx

name: Jerry Brito
tweet: @fubuloubu @jahimes According to the press release from the House Financial Services leadership, yes. https://t.co/Ju0Hhx4dnp

name: Jerry Brito
tweet: 13/ It's time to call your member of Congress and ask that they take action to make sure that notice and comment and duration limitations are not removed from 31 U.S.C. ¬ß 5318A as the America COMPETES Act would do.

name: Jerry Brito
tweet: 12/ It still strips out *all* administrative process and duration limitations on the Secretary‚Äôs power to condition or prohibit transactions at financial institutions associated with primary money laundering concerns.

name: Jerry Brito
tweet: 11/ After alerting folks in the House and Senate of that amendment's unintended consequences, it was removed from the final bill that passed. Unfortunately it's back verbatim without any improvements.

name: Jerry Brito
tweet: 10/ This provision was first introduced as an amendment to the national Defense Authorization Act last year by Rep. @jahimes. https://t.co/Fe4x8XnkEk https://t.co/ogpFB2qK1o

name: Jerry Brito
tweet: 9/ It empowers the Secretary to prohibit any (or indeed all) cryptocurrency transactions (or any other kind of transaction) without any process, rulemaking, or limitation on the duration of the prohibition.

name: Jerry Brito
tweet: 8/ If adopted into law, this provision would be disaster not just for crypto but for privacy and democratic public process related to *all* types of financial transactions.

name: Jerry Brito
tweet:
7/ The new provision would do three things:

-Add "certain transmittal of funds" to the list of things that can be banned by the Secretary

-Eliminate all public notice and comment requirements

-Eliminate the 120-day limitation for measures imposed without regulation https://t.co/crGCnPoHn9

name: Jerry Brito
tweet: 6/ While not full due process, these limitations at least alert the public and gives the public some opportunity to comment on a special measure's merit or constitutionality.

name: Jerry Brito
tweet: 5/ First, the law requires that Treasury engage in a public rulemaking before instituting a prohibition. Second, the secretary can impose a surveillance special measure through a simple order, but its duration is limited to 120 days and must be accompanied by a public rulemaking.

name: Jerry Brito
tweet: 4/ "Special measures" authority is vast power that the Secretary of the Treasury has today, so in the current statute there are checks on that power.

name: Jerry Brito
tweet: 3/ Bank Secrecy Act ¬ß5318A allows the Secretary to identify a "primary money laundering concern" and take "special measures" to (1) require financial institutions to report information on the concern, and/or (2) prohibit FIs from maintaining accounts related to the concern.
